Part 3: Working with Categorical Variables¶

In this section we create lists to instruct Pandas about the correct order of our categorical classes

In [9]:
clarity_levels = ['I1','SI2','SI1','VS2','VS1','VVS2','VVS1','IF']
cut_levels = ['J','I','H','G','F','E','D']
color_levels = ['Fair','Good','Very Good','Ideal','Premium']

Below we utilize these lists to inform Pandas how to rank items in the correct order.

In [10]:
diamonds.clarity = pd.Categorical(diamonds.clarity, clarity_levels)
diamonds.color = pd.Categorical(diamonds.color, color_levels)
diamonds.cut = pd.Categorical(diamonds.cut, cut_levels)

Below contains a list of colors that will be utilized in later data visualizations

In [11]:
clarity_pal = ['b','g','r','c','m','yellow','orange','purple']
cut_pal = ['b','g','r','c','m','yellow','orange',]
color_pal =['b','g','r','c','m',]

Part 5: Scatterplots of Price Against Carat¶

This problem probes the correltation between price and carat using scatter plots

In [16]:
plt.figure(figsize=[8,6])
plt.scatter(x=diamonds.loc[:,'carat'], y=diamonds.loc[:,'price'], s=20, alpha=0.4, 
            color='orchid')
plt.xlabel('Carat Size')
plt.ylabel('Price (in $)')
plt.title('Relationship between Diamond Price and Carat Size')
plt.show()

Below we expand upon the plot by incorporating diamond clarity as a categorical variable represented by the color of the point.

In [17]:
plt.figure(figsize=[12,6])
for i in range(len(clarity_pal)):
    plt.scatter(x=diamonds.loc[diamonds.loc[:,'clarity']==clarity_levels[i],'carat'], y=diamonds.loc[diamonds.loc[:,'clarity']==clarity_levels[i],'price'], s=20, alpha=0.4, 
            color=clarity_pal[i], label=clarity_levels[i])
plt.xlabel('Carat Size')
plt.ylabel('Price (in $)')
plt.title('Relationship between Diamond Price and Carat Size')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

The below group of plots display the same relationship but breakout subplots according to clarity levels.

In [18]:
plt.figure(figsize=[12,6])

for i in range(len(clarity_pal)):
    plt.subplot(2,4,i+1)
    plt.scatter(x=diamonds.loc[diamonds.loc[:,'clarity']==clarity_levels[i],'carat'], y=diamonds.loc[diamonds.loc[:,'clarity']==clarity_levels[i],'price'], s=20, alpha=0.4, 
            color=clarity_pal[i], label=clarity_levels[i])
    plt.xlabel('Carat Size')
    plt.ylabel('Price (in $)')
    plt.title('Price vs Carat Size for Clarity '+clarity_levels[i])
    plt.xlim([0,4])
    plt.ylim([0,20000])
    plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Part 6: Applying Logarithmic Transformations¶

Now we will explore the same price v carat relationship but using logarithmic transformations. This begins by adding two columns to the diamonds dataframe so we can store the transformed data.

In [19]:
diamonds.loc[:,'ln_carat']=np.log(diamonds.loc[:,'carat'])
diamonds.loc[:,'ln_price']=np.log(diamonds.loc[:,'price'])

Below are the histograms to explore the price carat relationship for our transformed variables

In [20]:
plt.figure(figsize=[12,4])
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
plt.hist(diamonds.loc[:,'price'],edgecolor='black', color='cornflowerblue', bins=20)
plt.xlabel('Price')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Histogram of Prices')

plt.subplot(1,2,2)
plt.hist(diamonds.loc[:,'ln_price'],edgecolor='black', color='cornflowerblue', bins=20)
plt.xlabel('Natural Log of Price')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Histogram of Log-Prices')
plt.show()

we now perform the same data visualization for the carats and natural log of carats

In [21]:
plt.figure(figsize=[12,4])
plt.subplot(1,2,1)
plt.hist(diamonds.loc[:,'carat'],edgecolor='black', color='cornflowerblue', bins=20)
plt.xlabel('Carat')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Histogram of Carat Sizes')

plt.subplot(1,2,2)
plt.hist(diamonds.loc[:,'ln_carat'],edgecolor='black', color='cornflowerblue', bins=20)
plt.xlabel('Natural Log of Carat Sizes')
plt.ylabel('Count')
plt.title('Histogram of Log-Carat Sizes')
plt.show()

Part 7: Scatterplot of Transformed Variables¶

Similar to Part 5, we will now display the transformed variables in a scatter plot displaying clarity values as categorical colors

plt.figure(figsize=[12,6])
for i in range(len(clarity_pal)):
    plt.scatter(x=diamonds.loc[diamonds.loc[:,'clarity']==clarity_levels[i],'ln_carat'], y=diamonds.loc[diamonds.loc[:,'clarity']==clarity_levels[i],'ln_price'], s=20, alpha=0.4,
